               <p>RICHARD MILLEN. I live in <placeName id="t18270913-188-crimeloc1066">Cow-cross-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18270913-188-crimeloc1066" type="placeName" value="Cow-cross-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18270913-188-crimeloc1066" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-188-off1064 t18270913-188-crimeloc1066"></join>; I am a <rs id="t18270913-188-viclabel1067" type="occupation">broker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-188-victim1771 t18270913-188-viclabel1067"></join>. On the 5th of August about six o'clock in the afternoon, this time-piece stood in my shop about six yards from the back part; I was in the parlour, and heard the shop door open; I went in, and the prisoner had moved this time-piece about four yards, and was putting it into a pail, which he had brought with him. When I saw him, he pretended that he wanted to sell the pail.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-188-person1772">
                  JAMES 
                  JERRY
               <interp inst="t18270913-188-person1772" type="surname" value="JERRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-188-person1772" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-188-person1772" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a watch-flutcher. I was returning home, and saw the prisoner with a pail in Cow-cross-street - I thought it was curious to carry it on a Sunday, and I watched him to the shop; I saw him with the timepiece in his hand.</p>
               <p>The prisoner put in a written defence, stating that he had gone to the shop to sell the pail, but denied having touched the time-piece.</p>
               <p>
